
The Two Pointer Technique is a problem-solving approach where two variables (pointers) are used to traverse or process data (usually arrays or strings) at the same time.
optimized way instead of using nested loops.

Using two indexes/pointers that usually: Start from different positions and Move toward each other OR move at different speeds

Why We Use It

👉 To reduce time complexity
👉 To avoid nested loops
👉 To improve performance

Converts : O(n²) → O(n)

1. Opposite Direction Pointers
 Used in:

    Reverse array

    Palindrome checking

    Pair sum in sorted array

2. Same Direction Pointers

 Used in:

    Remove duplicates

    Move zeros

    Partition problems


| Situation             | Use           |
| --------------------- | ------------- |
| Traversing array/list | `for`         |
| Known iteration count | `for`         |
| Two pointer problems  | `while`       |
| Condition based loops | `while`       |
| Input loops           | `while`       |
| Infinite loops        | `while(true)` |

